%N A395393 Decimal expansion of the volume of the solid of revolution formed by rotating a unit half-width lemniscate of Bernoulli about the horizontal axis.
%C A395393 The lemniscate of Bernoulli can be described by (x^2 + y^2)^2 = a^2*(x^2 - y^2) in Cartesian coordinates, or r^2 = a^2*cos(2*phi) in polar coordinates, where a is the half-width. Here we take a = 1.
%D A395393 N. P. Bali and Usha Paul, A Textbook of Engineering Mathematics: for B.E., B.Tech. Semester I, Laxmi Publications (P) Ltd, 8th ed., 2014, pp. 142-145.
%H A395393 Mandeep Beniwal, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MBXioI6FQhM">Volume of solid of revolution of lemniscate</a>, Smart study helper, YouTube video, 2021.
%H A395393 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395393/a395393.png">Illustration of the solid of revolution</a>.
%H A395393 Filo, <a href="https://askfilo.com/user-question-answers-smart-solutions/find-the-volume-of-the-solid-generated-by-the-revolution-of-3332363435303032">Find the volume of the solid generated by the revolution of the lemniscate...</a>.
%H A395393 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Lemniscate.html">Lemniscate</a>.
%H A395393 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SolidofRevolution.html">Solid of Revolution</a>.
%H A395393 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemniscate_of_Bernoulli">Lemniscate of Bernoulli</a>.
%H A395393 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_of_revolution">Solid of revolution</a>.
%F A395393 Equals (3*sqrt(2)*arcsinh(1) - 2) * Pi/12.
%F A395393 Equals (3*sqrt(2)*log(1+sqrt(2)) - 2) * Pi/12.
%e A395393 0.455361142379842578562411139680602786173346170098182...
